# [OAUTH](../wg/oauth.html) - IETF 125 Meeting Minutes

## Summary
The OAUTH Working Group met at IETF 125 to discuss the progress of core specifications, security updates, and several new proposals, particularly focusing on AI agent workflows and enterprise federation. Key milestones included the advancement of OAuth 2.1, the nearing of Working Group Last Call (WGLC) for First-Party Applications, and the introduction of security best current practice (BCP) updates addressing new attack vectors.

## Key Discussion Points

### 1. OAuth 2.1
**Reference:** [draft-ietf-oauth-v2-1](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/draft-ietf-oauth-v2-1/)
**Slides:** [OAuth 2.1](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/125/materials/slides-125-oauth-oauth-21-00)
**Presenter:** Aaron Parecki

*   **Mix-up Mitigation (Issue 233):** Discussion centered on whether to mandate the `iss` (issuer) response parameter. Aaron Parecki noted that while it is easy for Authorization Servers (AS) to add, clients must be able to validate it against metadata. Kaisen Lua raised concerns that not all clients use metadata, potentially hindering mitigation.
*   **PKCE 'Plain' Method:** The group discussed forbidding the `plain` challenge mode in PKCE. John Bradley and others supported the removal, noting that SHA-256 is universally available in environments capable of running OAuth 2.1.

### 2. Client ID Metadata Document
**Reference:** [draft-ietf-oauth-client-id-metadata-document](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/draft-ietf-oauth-client-id-metadata-document/)
**Slides:** [Client ID Metadata Document](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/125/materials/slides-125-oauth-client-id-metadata-document-00)
**Presenter:** Aaron Parecki

*   **Security & SSRF:** Updates include prohibiting redirects during metadata fetching and authenticating the user before fetching metadata to mitigate SSRF risks.
*   **URI Schemes:** Discussion on whether to restrict `client_uri` and `logo_uri` to HTTPS or allow Data URIs for optimization.
*   **JWK vs. JWKS URI:** Guidance is needed on whether the AS must support both embedded keys and linked key sets.

### 3. OAuth 2.0 for First-Party Applications
**Reference:** [draft-ietf-oauth-first-party-apps](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/draft-ietf-oauth-first-party-apps/)
**Slides:** [OAuth for First Party Apps](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/125/materials/slides-125-oauth-oauth-for-first-party-apps-00)
**Presenter:** Aaron Parecki

*   **PAR Integration:** The editors recommended against extending Pushed Authorization Requests (PAR) for this draft, as it would require significant modifications to PAR's response structure. Brian Campbell supported this decision.
*   **Maturity:** The draft has multiple implementations. Aaron Parecki requested WGLC following a final resolution of the PAR issue.

### 4. Identity Assertion JWT Authorization Grant
**Reference:** [draft-ietf-oauth-identity-assertion-authz-grant](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/draft-ietf-oauth-identity-assertion-authz-grant/)
**Slides:** [Identity Assertion Authorization Grant](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/125/materials/slides-125-oauth-identity-assertion-authorization-grant-00)
**Presenter:** Aaron Parecki

*   **New Features:** Recent updates added support for DPoP, Rich Authorization Requests (RAR), and the use of Refresh Tokens as subject tokens to handle expired ID tokens in enterprise SSO scenarios.
*   **Terminology:** The term "Cross-App Access" (XAA) was discussed as an informal name for the functionality.

### 5. Updates to OAuth 2.0 Security Best Current Practice
**Reference:** [draft-ietf-oauth-security-topics-update](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/draft-ietf-oauth-security-topics-update/)
**Slides:** [Updates to OAuth 2.0 Security Best Current Practice](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/125/materials/slides-125-oauth-updates-to-oauth-20-security-best-current-practice-00)
**Presenter:** Kaisen Lua

*   **New Attack Vectors:** The draft addresses Audience Injection, Cross Toolkit Account Takeover (CULT), and Cross-User Session Fixation.
*   **Mix-up Mitigation:** Kaisen Lua argued that existing issuer-based defenses are often insufficient in real-world SaaS/connector ecosystems and proposed alternative client-side identifiers.

### 6. RAR Metadata and Error Signaling
**Slides:** [RAR Metadata and Error Signaling](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/125/materials/slides-125-oauth-rar-metadata-and-error-signaling-00)
**Presenter:** Yaron Sheffer

*   **Discovery:** Proposed a new AS endpoint to describe supported RAR types and schemas, as the current RAR specification has limited metadata.
*   **Remediation:** Introduced a pattern where a Resource Server (RS) can return an actionable RAR object to a client upon an "insufficient authorization" error.

### 7. Native Clients with Federation
**Slides:** [OAuth 2.0 for native clients with federation](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/125/materials/slides-125-oauth-oauth-20-for-native-clients-with-federation-00)
**Presenter:** Yaron Sheffer

*   **Profile of First-Party Apps:** This work extends [draft-ietf-oauth-first-party-apps](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/draft-ietf-oauth-first-party-apps/) to support native app-to-app flows across federated trust domains, specifically targeting use cases in the Swiss government and European banking.

### 8. Additional Hash Algorithms for OAuth 2.0
**Slides:** [Additional Hash Algorithms for OAuth 2.0](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/125/materials/slides-125-oauth-additional-hash-algorithms-for-oauth-20-00)
**Presenter:** Aaron Parecki (for Filip Skokan)

*   **Regulatory Compliance:** The draft introduces SHA-512 for PKCE, DPoP, and MTLS to satisfy CNSA 2.0 requirements which prohibit SHA-256 in certain environments.
*   **Negotiation:** Brian Campbell and Justin Richer questioned the need for complex negotiation, suggesting that the existing extension points are sufficient.

### 9. OAuth SPIFFE Client Authentication
**Reference:** [draft-ietf-oauth-spiffe-client-auth](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/draft-ietf-oauth-spiffe-client-auth/)
**Slides:** [OAuth SPIFFE Client Authentication](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/125/materials/slides-125-oauth-oauth-spiffe-client-authentication-00)
**Presenter:** Michael Frasier

*   **Alignment:** The draft aims to align SPIFFE SVIDs (X.509 and JWT) with existing OAuth assertion and MTLS frameworks, as well as the new [draft-ietf-oauth-attestation-based-client-auth](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/draft-ietf-oauth-attestation-based-client-auth/).

